@node Starting "Getting to know your way around"

	As you are reading this, we shall assume you are not familiar with this software, but do not
	let that put you off, the choices that can be made here are well explained, and very easy 
	to understand. Lets start with the basics:

	In order to access the configuration pages, you need to click the @{i}Options >>@{ui} button.

	This opens the configuration pages, and they are divided up into sections, as you can see 
	by the tabs at the top of the section.

	The five sections are: 

	@{"  General  " Link "General"} @{"  Display  " Link "Display"} @{"  Resources  " Link "Resources"} @{"  Programs  " Link "programs"} and @{"  Experience  " Link "Experience"}			

	Each one is described in more detail in the relevant section. Click on the links of interest.

	The whole GUI is now keyboard controllable in V1.1, and you can find the corresponding 
	key in the text close to the gadget. It is the letter which is underscored, like this @{u}S@{uu}.
	Pressing the highlighted key has the same effect as clicking on the gadget with the mouse.

@endnode

@node Choosing "Selecting profiles"


	As of V1.4, there are now multiple ways in which saved profiles can be 
	loaded into RDesktop.

	As described elsewhere, the @{i}Open... @{ui}button can be used on the @{"General" Link general}
	settings page. This will load a profile from any location you choose 
	in the file requester.

	A profile can be automatically loaded by setting the name of it as the 
	default in the @{"tooltypes" Link "tooltypes"}.

	On the initial display you will notice a new chooser gadget next to the
	@{i}Computer @{ui}gadget. Here you will find a list of all of the profiles that
	are stored in the same directory as RDesktop. By selecting any of
	these profiles will automatically load in the settings configured in
	the profile of the same name.

	If you know the name of the profile you want to load, you can simply type
	its name into the @{i}Computer @{ui}gadget, and again it will be loaded and
	its settings ready to be used.

@endnode

@node general "The General settings"

	The settings you see in here are all relevant to the connection to a remote computer. The
	entry gadget for the @{i}Computer @{ui}can have different contents, for example:

		You can specify the IP address of the computer you wish to connect to. This is the
		internet address in octal form (don't worry if you don't understand this) like this:

		@{b}195.275.23.97@{ub}

		All computers on a network, whether it be on the internet, or in your office are 
		recognised by a number such as this. In order to make it easier for us humans, 
		we have devised a way of describing network computers by names, like this:

		@{b}www.rdesktop.org@{ub} or @{b}www.amigaworld.net@{ub}

		Basically they both come down to the same thing, and will allow you to connect to a 
		remote computer, and transfer the desktop from it.
		
	In order to @{i}logon @{ui}to the remote computer, you can specify your username and password
	in their respective gadgets, this saves having to enter it into the logon prompt once 
	connected.

	You may also need to fill in the @{i}Domain @{ui}entry too, ask your network administrator about 
	this if you are unsure.

	The checkbox for @{i}Save my password @{ui}is to allow the password you entered above to be saved 
	in the profile. Which brings us nicely to the next two buttons.

	The @{i}Save As... @{ui}button allows you to save a profile. A profile is the collection of all the 
	information you will enter into the configuration pages that apply to this particular 
	remote computer. This will be saved with the name you specify, and it can be recalled at 
	any time by using the @{i}Open... @{ui}button. You can import profiles from anywhere by using the 
	resulting file requester. Profiles are stored in the current directory to RDesktop. There is more
	information on the importing of profiles in the @{" Selecting profiles " Link "choosing"} section.

	You will notice that once you load in a profile, its name is displayed on the window title bar.

	See also the sections on: 
	@{"  Display  " Link "Display"} @{" Resources  " Link "Resources"} @{" Programs  " Link "Programs"} and @{"  Experience  " Link "Experience"}
	for more configuration options.

@endnode

@node Display "The Display settings"

	The display setings are quite straight forward, and these setting specify how the remote 
	desktop is displayed on your local screen.

	First is the @{i}Remote desktop size @{ui}setting. Here you can set what size you want the window 
	to appear.

	The first four settings will create a window on your Workbench with the sizes set out in 
	the selection you make. The last setting, @{i}Full Screen@{ui}, will open the remote desktop on a 
	custom screen. You can select the screenmode for the remote desktop using the gadget to the
	right of the screensize selection. By selecting the mode here, it can be saved into the profile
	so that this remote computer will always open with this screenmode.You can also leave the
	screenmode unset, and you will be prompted for the screen mode when RDesktop connects to the 
	remote computer. This setting is temporary, and only applies to this particular connection.

	You may also notice the @{i}Center window on screen @{ui} control. This will set the window
	to the center of the screen if it is smaller than the screen. Without this option selected, the 
	window will appear at the upper left corner, and only works when the remote desktop is to 
	appear in a window. This option will be disabled for @{i}Full Screen @{ui}selections.

	You can also set the number of colours you wish to use in the next entry under @{i}Colours. @{ui} 
	Choices vary from 8bit (256 colours) up to 24bit (16million colours). If you are setting a custom 
	screen for display, the colour depth is taken from the screen mode you choose, and this option will 
	have no effect, and will be disabled for @{i}Full Screen @{ui}options.

	See also the sections on: 
	@{"  General  " Link "General"} @{" Resources  " Link "Resources"} @{" Programs  " Link "Programs"} and @{"  Experience  " Link "Experience"}
	for more configuration options.

@endnode

@node Resources "Machine resources"

	This section deals with ways in which the two machines interact, and what you can set 
	or apply.

	Firstly is the ability to retarget the audio from the remote computer. This means that 
	any sounds you may have heard on that machine, will be heard through the speakers 
	on your local machine, and this is activated by the use of the selection 
	@{i}Bring to this computer @{ui}.

	You can also set the AHI unit to use, normally unit zero is fine.

	In the second section, you can supress the mouse events being sent to the remote
	computer, and this again is set via this checkbox. By no sending mouse events
	to the remote computer will disable the facility of positional data being sent, which 
	will disable dragging of icons and slider bars, amongst others. Although an 
	inconvenience,	it does save a considerable amount on bandwidth, and will speed 
	up a slow connection.

	See also the sections on: 
	@{"  General  " Link "General"} @{" Display  " Link "Display"} @{" Programs  " Link "Programs"} and @{"  Experience  " Link "Experience"}
	for more configuration options.

@endnode

@node Programs "Interacting Programs with RDesktop"

	Should you wish to launch an external program prior to connecting to the remote computer,
	You can do so here.
	
	You enter in the full path and name of the program you want to run into the entry gadget
	at the lower end of the group.

	You can then tell RDesktop to run it with the checkbox above, setting it to ticked means 
	the program will be started.

	See also the sections on: 
	@{"  General  " Link "General"} @{" Display  " Link "Display"} @{" Resources  " Link "Resources"} and @{"  Experience  " Link "Experience"}
	for more configuration options.

@endnode

@node Experience "How your network speed effects your experience"

	This control panel is all about how you experience the remote computer. The faster your
	network connection, the better your enjoyment will be.

	There are four settings here, ranging from slow modem, to fast ethernet network, and each 
	one has a different effect on what is, and what is not, transmitted. Slow connections would 
	be drowned by the amount of information flowing, so RDesktop can opt to not send certain
	information across the network in order to speed things up. Below is a table of what is
	omitted at each speed.

			LAN  		This is the fatest speed, and allows the transmission of all 
					aspects of the remote computer.

			DSL		This is slightly slower, so in order to speed things up, it 
					turns off the desktop background.

			56K		This is the faster of the two modem settings, but to speed 
					this up, the background, window contents during dragging 
					and window/menu animations are skipped.

			28K8		This is the least most spectacular connection speed, and 
					nearly everything is sacrificed for speed. You get just the 
					bare minimum to work with.


	The other @{i}Compatibilty @{ui}control allows RDesktop to run on the older servers that
	require the earlier system.

	New in V1.1 is the @{i}Encryption @{ui} setting. This allows you to specify whether RDesktop
	should encrypt the data being transferred. This will also include your logon details to the 
	remote computer, and they could be visible to other computers. Make sure, if you are
	connecting via the Internet, or on an open network, encryption is enabled to be as secure
	as possible.

	See also the sections on: 
	@{"  General  " Link "General"} @{" Display  " Link "Display"} @{" Resources  " Link "Resources"} and @{"  Programs  " Link "Programs"}
	for more configuration options.

@endnode

@node ToolTypes "Configuration via tooltypes"

	Currently, there is only one tooltype, and that specifies what you want your default
	profile to be.

	First create your profile from within the configuration options pages, then use the 	
	@{i}Save As... @{ui}button to save it. You will need to specify a name in the file
	requester that appears. This will then be saved into the RDesktop directory.

	By editing the tooltype to specify the name of the profile you created, you can
	set RDesktopGUI to load this profile each time it starts up. The tooltype is like this:

		DEFAULT = <name of your profile>

	Saving your default profile with the name @{b}Default@{ub} will save you having
	to alter any tooltypes, this is already set for you.

@endnode

@node Installation "How and where"

	Installation is very straight forward. Install all files in this archive into the
	same directory as your RDesktop executable, and thats it. Run RDesktopGUI 
	and create your first profile.

	The images directory is needed for in-program graphics, please make sure you install 
	this too.

@endnode

